Indonesia's foreign minister announced a summit on January 6 to address the aftermath of Asia's natural disaster, with 23 countries and major organizations invited.
The focus is on handling the earthquake and tsunami impact, with Japan and Uzbekistan sending aid.
China also dispatched relief goods to Indonesia, while Australia pledged a historic 1 billion Australian dollars in assistance.
Japan committed to increasing aid to Aceh and North Sumatra provinces.
The United Nations World Food Program is airlifting food to Sumatra, with Bangladesh sending high-energy biscuits to Indonesia and Sri Lanka for tsunami victims.
